      <section id="faq" class="bg-slate-50 border-y border-slate-200">
        <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 py-14">
          <h2 class="text-3xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-slate-900 text-center">
            Frequently asked questions
          </h2>
          <p class="mt-3 text-center text-slate-600">
            Common questions about BTU sizing and air conditioner capacity.
          </p>

          <div class="mt-8 space-y-3">
            <details class="group rounded-xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-5">
              <summary class="flex items-center justify-between cursor-pointer font-semibold text-slate-900">
                How many BTUs do I need per square foot?
                <svg
                  class="h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-blue-600 transition-transform group-open:rotate-45"
                  fill="none"
                  stroke="currentColor"
                  stroke-width="2"
                  viewBox="0 0 24 24"
                >
                  <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M12 4v16m8-8H4"></path>
                </svg>
              </summary>
              <p class="mt-3 text-slate-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">
                A common rule of thumb is about <strong>20 BTU per square foot</strong> for cooling in a moderate climate with 8-foot ceilings. So a 600 sq ft space needs roughly 12,000 BTU, or one ton. This baseline rises in hot, sunny, or poorly insulated spaces and falls in cool, shaded, well-sealed ones — which is exactly what the calculator above adjusts for.
              </p>
            </details>

            <details class="group rounded-xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-5">
              <summary class="flex items-center justify-between cursor-pointer font-semibold text-slate-900">
                What size air conditioner do I need for a 1,500 square foot house?
                <svg
                  class="h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-blue-600 transition-transform group-open:rotate-45"
                  fill="none"
                  stroke="currentColor"
                  stroke-width="2"
                  viewBox="0 0 24 24"
                >
                  <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M12 4v16m8-8H4"></path>
                </svg>
              </summary>
              <p class="mt-3 text-slate-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">
                Using the 20 BTU per square foot rule, 1,500 sq ft works out to about <strong
                  >30,000 BTU, or roughly 2.5 tons</strong
                >, as a starting point. After accounting for climate, sun, insulation, and occupancy it typically lands between 2.5 and 3 tons. Enter your exact details in the calculator above for a tailored number.
              </p>
            </details>

            <details class="group rounded-xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-5">
              <summary class="flex items-center justify-between cursor-pointer font-semibold text-slate-900">
                How do I convert BTU to tons?
                <svg
                  class="h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-blue-600 transition-transform group-open:rotate-45"
                  fill="none"
                  stroke="currentColor"
                  stroke-width="2"
                  viewBox="0 0 24 24"
                >
                  <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M12 4v16m8-8H4"></path>
                </svg>
              </summary>
              <p class="mt-3 text-slate-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">
                One ton of cooling equals <strong>12,000 BTU per hour</strong>. To convert, divide the BTU figure by 12,000 — for example, 36,000 BTU ÷ 12,000 = 3 tons. The calculator does this automatically and rounds up to the nearest standard system size.
              </p>
            </details>

            <details class="group rounded-xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-5">
              <summary class="flex items-center justify-between cursor-pointer font-semibold text-slate-900">
                Is it better to oversize or undersize an AC unit?
                <svg
                  class="h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-blue-600 transition-transform group-open:rotate-45"
                  fill="none"
                  stroke="currentColor"
                  stroke-width="2"
                  viewBox="0 0 24 24"
                >
                  <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M12 4v16m8-8H4"></path>
                </svg>
              </summary>
              <p class="mt-3 text-slate-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">
                <strong>Neither.</strong> An oversized unit short-cycles — cooling the air fast but not running long enough to remove humidity, which wastes energy and wears out the compressor. An undersized unit runs constantly and never quite keeps up. Right-sizing (what this calculator estimates) gives the best comfort, efficiency, and equipment life.
              </p>
            </details>

            <details class="group rounded-xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-5">
              <summary class="flex items-center justify-between cursor-pointer font-semibold text-slate-900">
                Does ceiling height affect how many BTUs I need?
                <svg
                  class="h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-blue-600 transition-transform group-open:rotate-45"
                  fill="none"
                  stroke="currentColor"
                  stroke-width="2"
                  viewBox="0 0 24 24"
                >
                  <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M12 4v16m8-8H4"></path>
                </svg>
              </summary>
              <p class="mt-3 text-slate-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">
                Yes. The standard 20 BTU per square foot assumes 8-foot ceilings. Taller ceilings mean more air volume to condition, so the calculator scales the load up proportionally — a 10-foot ceiling adds roughly <strong>25%</strong> to the requirement.
              </p>
            </details>

            <details class="group rounded-xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-5">
              <summary class="flex items-center justify-between cursor-pointer font-semibold text-slate-900">
                How accurate is this BTU calculator vs. a Manual J load calculation?
                <svg
                  class="h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-blue-600 transition-transform group-open:rotate-45"
                  fill="none"
                  stroke="currentColor"
                  stroke-width="2"
                  viewBox="0 0 24 24"
                >
                  <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M12 4v16m8-8H4"></path>
                </svg>
              </summary>
              <p class="mt-3 text-slate-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">
                This tool gives a fast, reliable ballpark using the same factors a contractor weighs first: area, climate, sun, insulation, and occupancy. A full <strong>ACCA Manual J</strong> calculation goes further — accounting for window types, orientation, duct losses, and air infiltration — and is required for permits and equipment warranties. Use this for quick planning and a Manual J for final installation.
              </p>
            </details>

            <details class="group rounded-xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-5">
              <summary class="flex items-center justify-between cursor-pointer font-semibold text-slate-900">
                Why does the number of people in a room matter?
                <svg
                  class="h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-blue-600 transition-transform group-open:rotate-45"
                  fill="none"
                  stroke="currentColor"
                  stroke-width="2"
                  viewBox="0 0 24 24"
                >
                  <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M12 4v16m8-8H4"></path>
                </svg>
              </summary>
              <p class="mt-3 text-slate-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">
                Each person gives off body heat — roughly <strong>600 BTU per hour</strong> of additional cooling load. The calculator assumes two occupants by default and adds for each extra person, which matters most in offices, gyms, and busy living areas.
              </p>
            </details>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

